│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineCalls.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.     │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe reproducer shows InstCombine changing a cttz    │
│ call's second argument (is_zero_poison) from false to true: call noundef i32  │
│ @llvm.cttz.i32(i32 %y, i1 false) becomes call noundef i32 @llvm.cttz.i32(i32  │
│ %y, i1 true). Alive2 reports the transformation is incorrect: for %y = 0, the │
│ original returns 32 (bitwidth) which is a defined integer satisfying the      │
│ noundef attribute; the transformed version produces poison (due to            │
│ is_zero_poison=true and zero input), violating noundef and triggering UB.     │
│ Thus InstCombine made the program less defined.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's         │
│ Log:\nThe first modification is in foldCttzCtlz(): setting operand 1 of cttz  │
│ from false to true under the heuristic: \"If ctlz/cttz is only used as a      │
│ shift amount, set is_zero_poison to true.\" This matches the pattern: single  │
│ use, operand1 == false, and single user is a shift (%res = shl i32 %x,        │
│ %cttz). No other analysis influenced this initial change. A second visit then │
│ adds a range attribute. The unsoundness originates solely from the first      │
│ change.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nThe heuristic assumes it's safe to make   │
│ the cttz/ctlz call produce poison for zero input because the only use is as a │
│ shift amount, and shifting by the original result (bitwidth) would produce    │
│ poison anyway. However, that reasoning ignores call attributes: the intrinsic │
│ call is marked noundef, which forbids returning poison. Changing              │
│ is_zero_poison to true introduces a possibility of poison when the input is   │
│ zero, violating noundef even if the ultimate use would turn the value into    │
│ poison later. The optimization lacks a guard against degrading definedness in │
│ presence of NoUndef. Correctness condition: we must not flip the flag unless  │
│ (a) we can prove the input is non-zero (handled later by existing             │
│ known-nonzero logic) or (b) the result is allowed to become poison (no        │
│ noundef). Missing check for Attribute::NoUndef causes the bug.\n\n4. Proposed │
│ Edit Point(s):\nEdit lines 506-509 in InstCombineCalls.cpp (foldCttzCtlz).    │
│ Add a guard to avoid applying this transformation when the return value has   │
│ NoUndef (noundef) attribute. Rationale: prevents introducing poison where     │
│ previously a defined integer was guaranteed, preserving semantic obligations  │
│ of noundef. We rely on later code (lines 606-613) to still flip the flag when │
│ input proven non-zero; that remains sound even with noundef because zero case │
│ cannot occur.\n\nProposed change (conceptual):\nCurrent:\n  // If ctlz/cttz   │
│ is only used as a shift amount, set is_zero_poison to true.\n  if             │
│ (II.hasOneUse() && match(Op1, m_Zero()) &&\n      match(II.user_back(),       │
│ m_Shift(m_Value(), m_Specific(&II))))\n    return IC.replaceOperand(II, 1,    │
│ IC.Builder.getTrue());\n\nPatched:\n  // If ctlz/cttz is only used as a shift │
│ amount, we can set is_zero_poison to true\n  // because shifting by the       │
│ bitwidth produces poison. However, do not do this if the\n  // call's result  │
│ is constrained by 'noundef' (NoUndef); that would introduce poison\n  // for  │
│ an otherwise defined zero input. The later known-nonzero logic will still\n   │
│ // flip the flag safely when zero cannot occur.\n  if (II.hasOneUse() &&      │
│ match(Op1, m_Zero()) &&\n      match(II.user_back(), m_Shift(m_Value(),       │
│ m_Specific(&II))) &&\n      !II.hasRetAttr(Attribute::NoUndef))\n    return   │
│ IC.replaceOperand(II, 1, IC.Builder.getTrue());\n\n(Implementation detail:    │
│ Attribute::NoUndef corresponds to 'noundef'; using hasRetAttr is consistent   │
│ with range check later.)\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe unsoundness arises from       │
│ disregarding the noundef return attribute when converting cttz/ctlz to        │
│ zero-poison form under a shift-only usage heuristic. Adding a guard to skip   │
│ this transformation for NoUndef results preserves definedness and fixes the   │
│ reported Alive2 counterexample while retaining the optimization for           │
│ unconstrained calls or those proven non-zero. This targeted change addresses  │
│ the root cause without impacting other foldCttzCtlz behaviors."})             │
