│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The reproducer shows InstCombine changing a cttz call's second argument       │
│ (is_zero_poison) from false to true: call noundef i32 @llvm.cttz.i32(i32 %y,  │
│ i1 false) becomes call noundef i32 @llvm.cttz.i32(i32 %y, i1 true). Alive2    │
│ reports the transformation is incorrect: for %y = 0, the original returns 32  │
│ (bitwidth) which is a defined integer satisfying the noundef attribute; the   │
│ transformed version produces poison (due to is_zero_poison=true and zero      │
│ input), violating noundef and triggering UB. Thus InstCombine made the        │
│ program less defined.                                                         │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The first modification is in foldCttzCtlz(): setting operand 1 of cttz from   │
│ false to true under the heuristic: "If ctlz/cttz is only used as a shift      │
│ amount, set is_zero_poison to true." This matches the pattern: single use,    │
│ operand1 == false, and single user is a shift (%res = shl i32 %x, %cttz). No  │
│ other analysis influenced this initial change. A second visit then adds a     │
│ range attribute. The unsoundness originates solely from the first change.     │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ The heuristic assumes it's safe to make the cttz/ctlz call produce poison for │
│ zero input because the only use is as a shift amount, and shifting by the     │
│ original result (bitwidth) would produce poison anyway. However, that         │
│ reasoning ignores call attributes: the intrinsic call is marked noundef,      │
│ which forbids returning poison. Changing is_zero_poison to true introduces a  │
│ possibility of poison when the input is zero, violating noundef even if the   │
│ ultimate use would turn the value into poison later. The optimization lacks a │
│ guard against degrading definedness in presence of NoUndef. Correctness       │
│ condition: we must not flip the flag unless (a) we can prove the input is     │
│ non-zero (handled later by existing known-nonzero logic) or (b) the result is │
│ allowed to become poison (no noundef). Missing check for Attribute::NoUndef   │
│ causes the bug.                                                               │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ Edit lines 506-509 in InstCombineCalls.cpp (foldCttzCtlz). Add a guard to     │
│ avoid applying this transformation when the return value has NoUndef          │
│ (noundef) attribute. Rationale: prevents introducing poison where previously  │
│ a defined integer was guaranteed, preserving semantic obligations of noundef. │
│ We rely on later code (lines 606-613) to still flip the flag when input       │
│ proven non-zero; that remains sound even with noundef because zero case       │
│ cannot occur.                                                                 │
│                                                                               │
│ Proposed change (conceptual):                                                 │
│ Current:                                                                      │
│   // If ctlz/cttz is only used as a shift amount, set is_zero_poison to true. │
│   if (II.hasOneUse() && match(Op1, m_Zero()) &&                               │
│       match(II.user_back(), m_Shift(m_Value(), m_Specific(&II))))             │
│     return IC.replaceOperand(II, 1, IC.Builder.getTrue());                    │
│                                                                               │
│ Patched:                                                                      │
│   // If ctlz/cttz is only used as a shift amount, we can set is_zero_poison   │
│ to true                                                                       │
│   // because shifting by the bitwidth produces poison. However, do not do     │
│ this if the                                                                   │
│   // call's result is constrained by 'noundef' (NoUndef); that would          │
│ introduce poison                                                              │
│   // for an otherwise defined zero input. The later known-nonzero logic will  │
│ still                                                                         │
│   // flip the flag safely when zero cannot occur.                             │
│   if (II.hasOneUse() && match(Op1, m_Zero()) &&                               │
│       match(II.user_back(), m_Shift(m_Value(), m_Specific(&II))) &&           │
│       !II.hasRetAttr(Attribute::NoUndef))                                     │
│     return IC.replaceOperand(II, 1, IC.Builder.getTrue());                    │
│                                                                               │
│ (Implementation detail: Attribute::NoUndef corresponds to 'noundef'; using    │
│ hasRetAttr is consistent with range check later.)                             │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The unsoundness arises from disregarding the noundef return attribute when    │
│ converting cttz/ctlz to zero-poison form under a shift-only usage heuristic.  │
│ Adding a guard to skip this transformation for NoUndef results preserves      │
│ definedness and fixes the reported Alive2 counterexample while retaining the  │
│ optimization for unconstrained calls or those proven non-zero. This targeted  │
│ change addresses the root cause without impacting other foldCttzCtlz          │
│ behaviors.                                                                    │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
