│ "  // If ctlz/cttz is only used as a shift amount, set is_zero_poison to      │
│ true.\n  // This is safe because shifting by the bitwidth is poison anyway.   │
│ However,\n  // do not apply this fold if the intrinsic's return value is      │
│ marked 'noundef'\n  // because flipping the flag would allow the intrinsic to │
│ produce poison for\n  // a zero input (when is_zero_poison=true) where        │
│ previously it was guaranteed\n  // to return a defined integer equal to the   │
│ bitwidth. That would violate the\n  // NoUndef contract and make the program  │
│ less defined. If we can later prove\n  // the input is non-zero, the fold     │
│ below guarded by known-nonzero logic will\n  // still canonicalize the flag   │
│ safely.\n  if (II.hasOneUse() && match(Op1, m_Zero()) &&\n                    │
│ match(II.user_back(), m_Shift(m_Value(), m_Specific(&II))) &&\n               │
│ !II.hasRetAttr(Attribute::NoUndef))\n    return IC.replaceOperand(II, 1,      │
│ IC.Builder.getTrue());", "new": "  // If ctlz/cttz is only used as a shift    │
│ amount, set is_zero_poison to true.\n  // This is safe because shifting by    │
│ the bitwidth is poison anyway. If the\n  // intrinsic is marked 'noundef',    │
│ dropping that attribute keeps the\n  // transformation sound (the result may  │
│ now become poison for a zero input).\n  if (II.hasOneUse() && match(Op1,      │
│ m_Zero()) &&\n      match(II.user_back(), m_Shift(m_Value(),                  │
│ m_Specific(&II)))) {\n    if (II.hasRetAttr(Attribute::NoUndef))\n            │
│ II.removeRetAttr(Attribute::NoUndef);\n    return IC.replaceOperand(II, 1,    │
│ IC.Builder.getTrue());\n  }"})                                                │
